    <sec id="Sec4">
      <title>Colored de Bruijn graphs</title>
      <p id="Par26">A <italic>string</italic> <italic>s</italic> is a sequence of characters over a finite, non-empty set, called <italic>alphabet</italic>. Its <italic>length</italic> is denoted by |<italic>s</italic>|, the character at position <italic>i</italic> by <italic>s</italic>[<italic>i</italic>], and the substring from position <italic>i</italic> through <italic>j</italic> by <italic>s</italic>[<italic>i</italic>..<italic>j</italic>]. A string of length <italic>k</italic> is called <italic>k</italic><italic>-mer</italic>.</p>
      <p id="Par27">We consider a <italic>genome</italic> as a set of strings over the DNA alphabet <inline-formula id="IEq34"><alternatives><tex-math id="M67">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\{A,C,G,T\}$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M68"><mml:mrow><mml:mo stretchy="false">{</mml:mo><mml:mi>A</mml:mi><mml:mo>,</mml:mo><mml:mi>C</mml:mi><mml:mo>,</mml:mo><mml:mi>G</mml:mi><mml:mo>,</mml:mo><mml:mi>T</mml:mi><mml:mo stretchy="false">}</mml:mo></mml:mrow></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="13015_2020_164_Article_IEq34.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula>. The <italic>reverse complement</italic> of a string <italic>s</italic> is <inline-formula id="IEq35"><alternatives><tex-math id="M69">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\overline{s}:=\overline{s[|s|]}\cdots \overline{s[1]}$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M70"><mml:mrow><mml:mover><mml:mi>s</mml:mi><mml:mo>¯</mml:mo></mml:mover><mml:mo>:</mml:mo><mml:mo>=</mml:mo><mml:mover><mml:mrow><mml:mi>s</mml:mi><mml:mo stretchy="false">[</mml:mo><mml:mo stretchy="false">|</mml:mo><mml:mi>s</mml:mi><mml:mo stretchy="false">|</mml:mo><mml:mo stretchy="false">]</mml:mo></mml:mrow><mml:mo>¯</mml:mo></mml:mover><mml:mo>⋯</mml:mo><mml:mover><mml:mrow><mml:mi>s</mml:mi><mml:mo stretchy="false">[</mml:mo><mml:mn>1</mml:mn><mml:mo stretchy="false">]</mml:mo></mml:mrow><mml:mo>¯</mml:mo></mml:mover></mml:mrow></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="13015_2020_164_Article_IEq35.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula>, where <inline-formula id="IEq36"><alternatives><tex-math id="M71">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\overline{A}:=T, \overline{C}:=G, \overline{G}:=C, \overline{T}:=A$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M72"><mml:mrow><mml:mover><mml:mi>A</mml:mi><mml:mo>¯</mml:mo></mml:mover><mml:mo>:</mml:mo><mml:mo>=</mml:mo><mml:mi>T</mml:mi><mml:mo>,</mml:mo><mml:mover><mml:mi>C</mml:mi><mml:mo>¯</mml:mo></mml:mover><mml:mo>:</mml:mo><mml:mo>=</mml:mo><mml:mi>G</mml:mi><mml:mo>,</mml:mo><mml:mover><mml:mi>G</mml:mi><mml:mo>¯</mml:mo></mml:mover><mml:mo>:</mml:mo><mml:mo>=</mml:mo><mml:mi>C</mml:mi><mml:mo>,</mml:mo><mml:mover><mml:mi>T</mml:mi><mml:mo>¯</mml:mo></mml:mover><mml:mo>:</mml:mo><mml:mo>=</mml:mo><mml:mi>A</mml:mi></mml:mrow></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="13015_2020_164_Article_IEq36.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula>.</p>
      <p id="Par28">An abstract data structure that is often used to efficiently store and process a collection of genomes is the <italic>colored de Bruijn graph (C-DBG)</italic> [<xref ref-type="bibr" rid="CR12">12</xref>]. It is a node-labeled graph (<italic>V</italic>, <italic>E</italic>, <italic>col</italic>) where each vertex <inline-formula id="IEq37"><alternatives><tex-math id="M73">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$v \in V$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M74"><mml:mrow><mml:mi>v</mml:mi><mml:mo>∈</mml:mo><mml:mi>V</mml:mi></mml:mrow></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="13015_2020_164_Article_IEq37.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> represents a <italic>k</italic>-mer associated with a set of colors <italic>col</italic>(<italic>v</italic>) representing the set of genomes the <italic>k</italic>-mer occurs in. A directed edge from <italic>v</italic> to <inline-formula id="IEq38"><alternatives><tex-math id="M75">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$v'$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M76"><mml:msup><mml:mi>v</mml:mi><mml:mo>′</mml:mo></mml:msup></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="13015_2020_164_Article_IEq38.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> exists if and only if for the corresponding <italic>k</italic>-mers <italic>x</italic> and <inline-formula id="IEq39"><alternatives><tex-math id="M77">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
